   201	
   202	## Safety Limits
   203	
   204	Initial simulation defaults should be conservative and parameterized:
   205	
   206	| Limit | Recommended default | Behavior |
   207	| --- | --- | --- |
   208	| Maximum altitude | `5.0 m` | Reject or clamp commands with `z < -5.0`. |
   209	| Minimum altitude | `0.5 m` while airborne | Reject commands too close to the ground unless landing mode is active. |
   210	| Maximum horizontal range | `5.0 m` radius from local origin | Reject or clamp commands where `sqrt(x*x + y*y) > 5.0`. |
   211	| Maximum horizontal speed | `2.0 m/s` commanded slew | Rate-limit target movement before publishing to PX4. |
   212	| Maximum vertical speed | `1.0 m/s` commanded slew | Rate-limit changes in NED `z`. |
   213	| Target jump limit | `1.5 m` per received command | Split larger jumps into intermediate setpoints or reject them. |
   214	| Target timeout | `1.0 s` for streaming clients | Hold last safe target when command input expires. |
   215	
   216	The current `uav_control_bridge` rejects commands outside these altitude, range,
   217	and target-jump limits. On target timeout it keeps publishing the last safe
   218	target and rate-limits timeout warnings to no more than once per timeout
   219	interval. It publishes the held safe target on `/uav/current_target` and the
   220	state on `/uav/control_state`. It also publishes `/uav/current_position` from
   221	valid PX4 local-position samples and `/uav/reached_target` using the configured
   222	reach tolerances.
   223	
   224	## Why LeRobot Should Not Publish `/fmu/in/*`
   225	
   226	LeRobot, vision modules, and task planners should not publish PX4 input topics
   227	directly because those topics are low-level flight-control interfaces:
   228	
   229	- `/fmu/in/trajectory_setpoint` expects PX4 NED semantics, valid timestamps,
   230	  feasible setpoints, and continuous streaming.
   231	- `/fmu/in/offboard_control_mode` must be synchronized with setpoint streaming
   232	  for PX4 offboard mode to remain valid.
   233	- `/fmu/in/vehicle_command` can arm, change modes, or land the vehicle.
   234	- Direct publishers can bypass altitude, range, speed, timeout, and emergency
   235	  stop checks.
   236	- Multiple direct publishers can race and send conflicting setpoints.
   237	
   238	The high-level `/uav/*` API gives learning and perception modules a small,
   239	auditable command surface. A single bridge node can validate commands, enforce
   240	limits, publish state, and own the PX4-specific details.
   241	
